{"title_page": "Ragnar Numelin", "text_new": "{{multiple issues|\n{{more footnotes|date=September 2017}}\n{{more citations needed|date=September 2017}}\n}}\n[[File:Ragnar-Numelin.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Ragnar Numelin end of the 1930s]]\n'''Ragnar Julius Numelin''' (28 September 1890 [[Turku]] \u2013 12 October 1972 [[Helsinki]]) was a Finnish diplomat and a non-fiction writer.\n\n== Personal life ==\nNumelin's parents were the Senator Gustaf Julius Ferdinand Nummelin and Anna Emelie Sourander. He graduated in 1911 as secondary school graduate and graduated as a Bachelor of Philosophy in 1913 and Licentiate in 1919.\n\n== Career ==\nNumelin was  assistant in the [[Helsinki University Library|University of Helsinki Library]] from 1914 to 1918 and served in the [[Ministry for Foreign Affairs (Finland)|Foreign Ministry]] for 35 years from 1918 and served as Consul General in [[Gothenburg]] 1945\u20131947, as Envoy in [[Brussels]] from 1947 to 1950 and in [[Vienna]] and in [[Prague]] in 1950\u20131953. Numelin published studies in the areas of diplomacy, sociology, ethnology, geography and graphology.<ref>[http://runeberg.org/aikalais/1934/0468.html Aikalaiskirja 1934 (Projekt Runeberg).]</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Numelin, Ragnar}}\n[[Category:Finnish diplomats]]\n[[Category:1890 births]]\n[[Category:1972 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Turku]]\n", "text_old": "{{multiple issues|\n{{more footnotes|date=September 2017}}\n{{more citations needed|date=September 2017}}\n}}\n[[File:Ragnar-Numelin.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Ragnar Numelin end of the 1930s]]\n'''Ragnar Julius Numelin''' (28 September 1890 [[Turku]] \u2013 12 October 1972 [[Helsinki]]) was a Finnish diplomat and a non-fiction writer.\n\n== Personal life ==\nNumelin\u00b4s parents were the Senator Gustaf Julius Ferdinand Nummelin and Anna Emelie Sourander. He graduated in 1911 as secondary school graduate and graduated as a Bachelor of Philosophy in 1913 and Licentiate in 1919.\n\n== Career ==\nNumelin was  assistant in the [[Helsinki University Library|University of Helsinki Library]] from 1914 to 1918 and served in the [[Ministry for Foreign Affairs (Finland)|Foreign Ministry]] for 35 years from 1918 and served as Consul General in [[Gothenburg]] 1945-1947, as Envoy in [[Brussels]] from 1947 to 1950 and in [[Vienna]] and in [[Prague]] in 1950-1953. Numelin published studies in the areas of diplomacy, sociology, ethnology, geography and graphology.<ref>[http://runeberg.org/aikalais/1934/0468.html Aikalaiskirja 1934 (Projekt Runeberg).]</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Numelin, Ragnar}}\n[[Category:Finnish diplomats]]\n[[Category:1890 births]]\n[[Category:1972 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Turku]]\n", "name_user": "Majavah", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up,typo(s) fixed: \u00b4s \u2192 's, 1945-1947 \u2192 1945\u20131947 (2)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ragnar_Numelin"}
{"title_page": "Calamus latifolius", "text_new": "{{Speciesbox\n|genus = Calamus (palm)\n|species = latifolius\n|authority = [[William Roxburgh|Roxb.]], Hort. Bengal. 73; Fl. Ind. iii. 775 (1832)<ref>{{cite web |title=Calamus latifolius Roxb. |url=https://www.ipni.org/n/665186-1 |website=International Plant Name Index (IPNI) |publisher=Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew |accessdate=16 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"palm\" />\n|synonyms = *<small>''Calamus dumetorum'' [[Henry Nicholas Ridley|Ridl.]]<ref name=\"powo\">{{cite web |title=Calamus latifolius Roxb. |url=http://powo.science.kew.org/taxon/urn:lsid:ipni.org:names:665186-1 |website=Plants of the World Online |publisher=Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew |accessdate=16 April 2020}}</ref>\n*''C. gregisectus'' [[Max Burret|Burret]]\n*''C. humilis'' Roxb.\n*''C. kerrianus'' [[Odoardo Beccari|Becc.]]\n*''C. loeiensis'' Hodel\n*''C. macracanthus'' [[ Thomas Anderson|T.Anderson]]\n*''C. palustris'' [[William Griffith|Griff.]]\n*''C. palustris'' var. ''cochinchinensis'' Becc.\n*''Palmijuncus humilis'' (Roxb.) [[Carl Ernst Otto Kuntze|Kuntze]]\n*''P. latifolius'' (Roxb.) Kuntze\n*''P. macracanthus (T.Anderson) Kuntze\n*''P. palustris (Griff.) Kuntze</small>}}\n\nA climbing plant, '''''Calamus latifolius''''', is part of a subfamily, [[Calamoideae]], whose members are usually called [[rattan|rattans]] in English, they are part of the [[Arecaceae]], or palm, family.\n\nIt is a moderately robust climber, growing up to 30m, usually with a cluster of stems and a leafsheath 3cm in diameter. Its leaves are curate, 2-3m long, with a prominenently kneed, spiny (3cm long) leafsheath. Both female and male flowers are simply decompound. The globose fruit is dull brown to blackish, with flattened fruit scales and a single seed.<ref name=\"palm\">{{cite web |title=Calamus latifolius Roxb., Fl. Ind. ed. 1832 , 3: 775 (1832) |url=http://www.palmweb.org/cdm_dataportal/taxon/e6e65b56-425a-4b29-8481-1a42f6243f48 |website=PALMweb |publisher=palmweb.org |accessdate=16 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"dyphon\">{{cite book |last1=[[Pauline Dy Phon]] |title=Plants Utilised In Cambodia/Plantes utilis\u00e9es au Cambodge |date=2000 |publisher=Imprimerie Olympic |location=Phnom Penh |page=121 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=InD2RAAACAAJ}}</ref>\nThe rattan grows in semi-dense forests of Cambodia and southern Vietnam.<ref name=\"dyphon\" />\nIn the [[D\u00e2mrei Mountains|Chu\u014fr Phnum D\u00e2mrei]] of southwestern Cambodia, they are characterized as growing on the edge of evergreen rainforest, usually as understorey, but becoming [[liana|lianas]] when mature.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Rundel |first1=Philip W. |title=Forest habitats and flora in Laos PDR, Cambodia, and Vietnam |date=1999 |publisher=Conservation Priorities In Indochina - WWF Desk Study, World Wide Fund for Nature, Indochina Programme Office |location=Hanoi |url=https://www.researchgate.net/profile/Philip_Rundel/publication/259623025_Forest_Habitats_and_Flora_in_Laos_PDR_Cambodia_and_Vietnam/links/02e7e52cef6a812cb4000000/Forest-Habitats-and-Flora-in-Laos-PDR-Cambodia-and-Vietnam.pdf |accessdate=16 April 2020}}</ref>\nIt also occurs as a large liana in the forest around [[Sangkae River|Steung Sangke]] in the northwest of Cambodia.\nGrowing in the [[Botanical Garden and Eco-Park, Sitakunda|Sitakunda Botanical Garden and Eco-park]], Bangladesh, it is regarded as under threat from illicit felling, over-harvesting for raw material and intentional fire hazards during the dry season.<ref name=\"dutta\">{{cite journal |last1=Dutta |first1=Shourav |last2=Hossain |first2=M. K. |last3=Chowdhury |first3=Pinaki |title=Non wood forest resources of Sitakunda Botanical Garden and Eco-park, Chittagong, Bangladesh |journal=Int. J. of Usuf. Mngt. |date=2014 |volume=15 |issue=2 |page=101-9 |publisher=Institute of Forestry and Environmental Sciences, University of Chittagong |location=Chittagong-4331 Bangladesh |issn=0972-3927}}</ref>\nIn India it occurs in moist lower hill forest communities up to 1000m, mostly near fresh water swamps.<ref name=\"palm\" />\n\nIt is native to: [[Peninsular Malaysia]]; [[Thailand]]; [[Cambodia]]; southern [[Vietnam]]; [[Laos]]; [[Andaman and Nicobar Islands]]; [[Myanmar]]; [[Bangladesh]]; [[Manipur]], [[Nagaland]], [[Arunachal Pradesh]], [[Assam]], [[Meghalaya]], [[Sikkim]], and [[West Bengal]] in [[India]]; and eastern [[Nepal]].<ref name=\"powo\" />\n\nVarious names by which the plant is known by include: ''phdau chhv\u00e8ang'', ''phdau chu:(r)'', [[Khmer language|Khmer]] (''phdau''=rattan).<ref name=\"dyphon\" />; ''korak'', ''budum'', Bangladesh.<ref name=\"dutta\" />; ''lee-ren'', [[Meitei language|Meitei]], Manipur; ''golar'', ''raiding'', [[Adi people|Adi]] language, Arunuchal Pradesh<ref name=\"angami\">{{cite journal |last1=Angami |first1=A. |last2=& others |title=Status and potential of wild edible plants of Arunuchal Pradesh |journal=Indian Journal of Traditional Knowledge |date=2006 |volume=5 |issue=4 |page=541-50 |url=http://nopr.niscair.res.in/bitstream/123456789/6948/1/IJTK%205%284%29%20%282006%29%20541-550.pdf |accessdate=16 April 2020}}</ref>;  ''korak bet'', ''horna bet'', India.<ref name=\"palm\" />\n\nThe fruit are eaten in Cambodia.<ref name=\"dyphon\" />\nIn the same country the canes are regarded as flexible and strong, and are much appreciated for basket making.\nOne of the many ingredients of ''[[Singju]]'' (prepared mainly of green vegetables with other plant parts like inflorescences and flowers, seeds, roots, rhizomes, etc., along with [non-vegetarian] or without [vegetarian] fermented dry fish, ''Ngari''), the [[Meitei people|Meitei]] people of Manipur use the young shoots, which can sell for 10-15 Rupees for a bunch of 3-5 young shoots in the local markets.<ref name=\"singh\">{{cite journal |last1=Singh |first1=P. K. |last2=Devi |first2=M. H. |title=Plants associated with Singju: a traditional salad delicacy of Meitei community of Manipur, India |journal=Pleione |date=2015 |volume=9 |issue=2 |page=409-18 |url=http://pleione.ehsst.org/journals/Pleione92/013%20Plants%20of%20Singju%20by%20Meiteis%20of%20Assam.pdf |accessdate=16 April 2020 |publisher=East Himalayan Society for Spermatophyte Taxonomy |issn=0973-9467}}</ref>\nIn Arunuchal Pradesh, the stems and fruit are eaten raw and are sold in markets.<ref name=\"angami\" />\nIn India the rattan is characterized as moderately strong, and is used for making rough baskets, walking sticks, and furniture frames, with the split canes used for weaving chair bottoms.<ref name=\"palm\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q15459579}}\n\n[[Category:Calamus (palm)|latifolius]]\n[[Category:Flora of Arunuchal Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Flora of Assam]]\n[[Category:Flora of Bangladesh]]\n[[Category:Flora of Cambodia]]\n[[Category:Flora of India (region)]]\n[[Category:Flora of Laos]]\n[[Category:Flora of Malaya]]\n[[Category:Flora of Malesia]]\n[[Category:Flora of Manipur]]\n[[Category:Flora of Meghalaya]]\n[[Category:Flora of Myanmar]]\n[[Category:Flora of Nagaland]]\n[[Category:Flora of Nepal]]\n[[Category:Flora of Peninsular Malaysia]]\n[[Category:Flora of Sikkim]]\n[[Category:Flora of Thailand]]\n[[Category:Flora of the Andaman Islands]]\n[[Category:Flora of the Nicobar Islands]]\n[[Category:Flora of Vietnam]]\n[[Category:Flora of West Bengal]]\n[[Category:Plants described in 1832]]\n\n{{palm-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Speciesbox\n|genus = Calamus (palm)\n|species = latifolius\n|authority = [[William Roxburgh|Roxb.]], Hort. Bengal. 73; Fl. Ind. iii. 775 (1832)<ref>{{cite web |title=Calamus latifolius Roxb. |url=https://www.ipni.org/n/665186-1 |website=International Plant Name Index (IPNI) |publisher=Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew |accessdate=16 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"palm\" />\n|synonyms = *<small>''Calamus dumetorum'' [[Henry Nicholas Ridley|Ridl.]]<ref name=\"powo\">{{cite web |title=Calamus latifolius Roxb. |url=http://powo.science.kew.org/taxon/urn:lsid:ipni.org:names:665186-1 |website=Plants of the World Online |publisher=Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew |accessdate=16 April 2020}}</ref>\n*''C. gregisectus'' [[Max Burret|Burret]]\n*''C. humilis'' Roxb.\n*''C. kerrianus'' [[Odoardo Beccari|Becc.]]\n*''C. loeiensis'' Hodel\n*''C. macracanthus'' [[ Thomas Anderson|T.Anderson]]\n*''C. palustris'' [[William Griffith|Griff.]]\n*''C. palustris'' var. ''cochinchinensis'' Becc.\n*''Palmijuncus humilis'' (Roxb.) [[Carl Ernst Otto Kuntze|Kuntze]]\n*''P. latifolius'' (Roxb.) Kuntze\n*''P. macracanthus (T.Anderson) Kuntze\n*''P. palustris (Griff.) Kuntze</small>}}\n\nA climbing plant, '''''Calamus latifolius''''', is part of a subfamily, [[Calamoideae]], whose members are usually called [[rattan|rattans]] in English, they are part of the [[Arecaceae]], or palm, family.\n\nIt is a moderately robust climber, growing up to 30m, usually with a cluster of stems and a leafsheath 3cm in diameter. Its leaves are curate, 2-3m long, with a prominenently kneed, spiny (3cm long) leafsheath. Both female and male flowers are simply decompound. The globose fruit is dull brown to blackish, with flattened fruit scales and a single seed.<ref name=\"palm\">{{cite web |title=Calamus latifolius Roxb., Fl. Ind. ed. 1832 , 3: 775 (1832) |url=http://www.palmweb.org/cdm_dataportal/taxon/e6e65b56-425a-4b29-8481-1a42f6243f48 |website=PALMweb |publisher=palmweb.org |accessdate=16 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"dyphon\">{{cite book |last1=[[Pauline Dy Phon]] |title=Plants Utilised In Cambodia/Plantes utilis\u00e9es au Cambodge |date=2000 |publisher=Imprimerie Olympic |location=Phnom Penh |page=121 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=InD2RAAACAAJ}}</ref>\nThe rattan grows in semi-dense forests of Cambodia and southern Vietnam.<ref name=\"dyphon\" />\nIn the [[D\u00e2mrei Mountains|Chu\u014fr Phnum D\u00e2mrei]] of southwestern Cambodia, they are characterized as growing on the edge of evergreen rainforest, usually as understorey, but becoming [[liana|lianas]] when mature.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Rundel |first1=Philip W. |title=Forest habitats and flora in Laos PDR, Cambodia, and Vietnam |date=1999 |publisher=Conservation Priorities In Indochina - WWF Desk Study, World Wide Fund for Nature, Indochina Programme Office |location=Hanoi |url=https://www.researchgate.net/profile/Philip_Rundel/publication/259623025_Forest_Habitats_and_Flora_in_Laos_PDR_Cambodia_and_Vietnam/links/02e7e52cef6a812cb4000000/Forest-Habitats-and-Flora-in-Laos-PDR-Cambodia-and-Vietnam.pdf |accessdate=16 April 2020}}</ref>\nIt also occurs as a large liana in the forest around [[Sangkae River|Steung Sangke]] in the northwest of Cambodia.\nGrowing in the [[Botanical Garden and Eco-Park, Sitakunda|Sitakunda Botanical Garden and Eco-park]], Bangladesh, it is regarded as under threat from illicit felling, over-harvesting for raw material and intentional fire hazards during the dry season.<ref name=\"dutta\">{{cite journal |last1=Dutta |first1=Shourav |last2=Hossain |first2=M. K. |last3=Chowdhury |first3=Pinaki |title=Non wood forest resources of Sitakunda Botanical Garden and Eco-park, Chittagong, Bangladesh |journal=Int. J. of Usuf. Mngt. |date=2014 |volume=15 |issue=2 |page=101-9 |publisher=Institute of Forestry and Environmental Sciences, University of Chittagong |location=Chittagong-4331 Bangladesh |issn=0972-3927}}</ref>\nIn India it occurs in moist lower hill forest communities up to 1000m, mostly near fresh water swamps.<ref name=\"palm\" />\n\nIt is native to: [[Peninsular Malaysia]]; [[Thailand]]; [[Cambodia]]; southern [[Vietnam]]; [[Laos]]; [[Andaman and Nicobar Islands]]; [[Myanmar]]; [[Bangladesh]]; [[Manipur]], [[Nagaland]], [[Arunachal Pradesh]], [[Assam]], [[Meghalaya]], [[Sikkim]], and [[West Bengal]] in [[India]]; and eastern [[Nepal]].<ref name=\"powo\" />\n\nVarious names by which the plant is known by include: ''phdau chhv\u00e8ang'', ''phdau chu:(r)'', [[Khmer language|Khmer]] (''phdau''=rattan).<ref name=\"dyphon\" />; ''korak'', ''budum'', Bangladesh.<ref name